26 December 2009 <!--DASHBot-->|url-status = live}}</ref><br />PS3: 8.2/10<ref name=\"ign-ps3review\" />\n<!-- Awards No limit -->\n| award1Pub = [[IGN|IGN UK]]\n| award1 = [[Game of the Year]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://uk.ign.com/videos/2010/12/10/best-games-of-2010-the-weekend-initiative |title=IGN UK's Best Games of 2010 - IGN Weekend Initiative - IGN Video |publisher=IGN |date=December 10, 2010 |accessdate=June 24, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111107061949/http://uk.ign.com/videos/2010/12/10/best-games-of-2010-the-weekend-initiative |archive-date=November 7, 2011 |url-status = live}}</ref>\n| award2Pub = [[GameSpot]]\n| award2 = Best Boss Fights<ref>{{cite web |url=http://uk.gamespot.com/best-of-2010/special-achievement/index.html?page=21 |title=Best Boss Fights - The Best Games of 2010 on GameSpot |website=GameSpot |accessdate=June 24, 2012 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121018035555/http://uk.gamespot.com/best-of-2010/special-achievement/index.html?page=21 |archivedate=October 18, 2012 }}</ref> and Best Original IP<ref>{{cite web |url=http://uk.gamespot.com/best-of-2010/special-achievement/index.html?page=20 |title=Best Original IP - The Best Games of 2010 on GameSpot |website=GameSpot |accessdate=2012-06-24 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121018035528/http://uk.gamespot.com/best-of-2010/special-achievement/index.html?page=20 |archivedate=2012-10-18 }}</ref>\n| award3Pub = [[GameTrailers]]\n| award3 = Best New IP<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gametrailers.com/video/best-new-game-of-the/708581 |title=GameTrailers Game Of The Year Awards 2010 Video Game, Best New IP HD &#124; Video Clip &#124; Game Trailers & Videos |website=GameTrailers |date=December 20, 2010 |accessdate=2012-06-24 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110919192347/http://www.gametrailers.com/video/best-new-game-of-the/708581 |archivedate=September 19, 2011 }}</ref>\n| award4Pub = [[Giant Bomb]]\n| award4 = Best Debut<ref name=\"giantbomb\">{{cite web |url=http://www.giantbomb.com/news/giant-bombs-game-of-the-year-2010-day-one/2800/ |title=Giant Bomb's Game of the Year 2010: Day One |publisher=Giant Bomb |date=2012-06-15 |accessdate=2012-06-24 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120901060206/http://www.giantbomb.com/news/giant-bombs-game-of-the-year-2010-day-one/2800/ |archive-date=2012-09-01 |url-status = live }}</ref>\n}}\n\n=== Press reception ===\nCritics generally lauded the graphical presentation and the title character - Cam Shea of ''[[IGN]]'' Australia praised the developing game in March 2009 as \"absolutely stunning-looking\" and \"a balls-out action game set amongst glorious European architecture\", and called its titular witch their \"new favourite videogame character ever\" - they compared her to ''Devil May Cry''{{'s}} protagonist Dante, commenting that she had his \"playfulness and versatility\", but with \"some of the most visually inventive combat\" they've seen.<ref name=\"ign-progress\" />  Similarly, ''[[GameSpy]]'''s Gerald Villoria praised the game in July that year as highly original to the point that it could end up like the poor-selling ''[[\u014ckami]]'' (another Kamiya-directed game) because \"the premise, the characters, the action sequences\" were different from anything he'd ever played, and called its lead a \"constantly moving\", \"remarkably multi-faceted\" character \"presented in an ultra-stylish way\".<ref name=\"gamespy-e32009\">{{cite web |last=Villoria |first=Gerald |url=http://xbox360.gamespy.com/xbox-360/bayonetta/992244p1.html |title=E3 2009: Bayonetta Preview |publisher=GameSpy |date=June 5, 2009 |accessdate=October 15, 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090611222653/http://xbox360.gamespy.com/xbox-360/bayonetta/992244p1.html |archive-date=June 11, 2009 |url-status = live }}</ref> \n\nThe PS3 and Xbox 360 versions in general were also commented on - a few days before ''Bayonetta''{{'s}} release, Japanese gaming publication ''[[Famitsu]]'' awarded the Xbox 360 version a perfect 40 out of 40, a relatively rare occurrence that many consider prestigious. The PlayStation 3 version received a slightly lower rating,<ref name=\"ign-famitsu2\">{{cite web|url=http://ps3.ign.com/articles/103/1037152p1.html|title=Bayonetta is Perfect|last=Gantayat|first=Anoop|date=October 21, 2009|publisher=IGN|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091024040918/http://ps3.ign.com/articles/103/1037152p1.html|archivedate=24 October 2009 <!--DASHBot-->|accessdate=October 21, 2009}}</ref> criticized for its lesser visual quality, frame rate and control problems compared to the Xbox 360 version.<ref name=\"1up-famitsu3\">{{cite web|url=http://www.1up.com/do/newsStory?cId=3176576|title=Famitsu Awards Xbox 360's Bayonetta Perfect Score|last=Bailey|first=Kat|date=October 20, 2009|website=1UP.com|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121016050940/http://www.1up.com/news/famitsu-awards-xbox-360-bayonetta|archivedate=October 16, 2012|accessdate=October 21, 2009}}</ref><ref name=\"1up-famitsu22\">{{cite web|url=http://www.1up.com/do/newsStory?cId=3176578|title=Japan Review Check: Tekken 6, Final Fantasy Gaiden|last=Gifford|first=Kevin|date=October 21, 2009|website=1UP.com|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120720173927/http://www.1up.com/news/japan-review-check-tekken-6_3|archivedate=July 20, 2012|accessdate=October 21, 2009}}</ref> At the 2009 Tokyo Game Show, Daniel Feit of [[Wired News|''Wired News'']] played both versions and felt that while the 360 version was \"a little brighter and more colorful\", the PS3 version's cutscenes resembled \"watching a movie through a sepia filter\".<ref name=\"wired-handson\">{{cite web|url=https://www.wired.com/gamelife/2009/09/bayonetta-preview/|title=Hands On: How Bayonetta Stacks Up on 360 vs. PS3|last=Feit|first=Daniel|date=September 24, 2009|work=[[Wired News]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091028131823/http://www.wired.com/gamelife/2009/09/bayonetta-preview/|archivedate=28 October 2009 <!--DASHBot-->|accessdate=October 11, 2009}}</ref> ''[[GameSpot]]''{{'}}s video review lamented duller graphics and inconsistent [[Frame rate|frame rates]] for its PS3 [[Porting|port]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamespot.com/ps3/action/bayonetta/index.html?tag=result;title;0|title=Gamespot - Bayonetta Reviews|date=January 7, 2010|website=GameSpot|accessdate=2010-04-08}}</ref> 1UP's staff again played a PS3 version for 15 minutes on the weekend of August 31 that year, at PlatinumGames's \"Feel Bayonetta\" event.  They said that it \"was very blurry\" compared to a 360 version displayed there, and that its [[frame rate]] \"was all over the place\", and as a result, it was \"often hard to keep track of the action [in one scene]\".<ref name=\"1up-feelbayonetta\">{{cite web|url=http://www.1up.com/do/newsStory?cId=3175838|title=Platinum Shows PS3 Bayonetta, Announces Demo|last=Epperson|first=Justin|date=August 31, 2009|website=1UP.com|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110622070721/http://www.1up.com/news/platinum-shows-ps3-bayonetta-announces|archivedate=June 4, 2011|accessdate=October 10, 2009}}</ref> Ryan Clements of ''IGN'' said that while the PS3 version was \"still a fun game\", it had \"a lot of problems\", mainly being \"the excessive slowdown and loading\".<ref name=\"ign-ps3review2\">{{cite web|url=http://ps3.ign.com/articles/105/1057012p1.html|title=Bayonetta Review (PlayStation 3)|last=Clements|first=Ryan|date=December 22, 2009|publisher=IGN|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091226035445/http://ps3.ign.com/articles/105/1057012p1.html|archivedate=26 December 2009 <!--DASHBot-->|accessdate=December 22, 2009}}</ref> \n\nThe gameplay and plot received general praise from critics - Matt Leone of ''[[1UP.com]]'' said of the pre-release version of the game's PS3 port that when he discovered he could \"hold down the final button in the string to continuously fire gunshots\" he observed that it looked \"incredibly cool when you kick someone and then keep your leg pointed at their face\".<ref name=\"1up-handson\" /> ''[[Edge (magazine)|Edge]]'' awarded the game a score of 10 out of 10, praising the game's combat system for both having depth and being able to be learnt easily. ''Edge'' singled out the upgrade from Normal to Hard difficulties as the point where the game transitions from \"the great to the legendary\", concluding that it was \"difficult to recall another third-person actioner\" that felt \"so worth mastering\".<ref name=\"edgereview2\">{{cite magazine|author=''Edge'' staff|date=Christmas 2009|title=Bayonetta|url=http://www.edge-online.com/reviews/review-bayonetta/|magazine=[[Edge (magazine)|Edge]]|location=[[Bath, Somerset|Bath]]|publisher=[[Future Publishing]]|issue=209|pages=90\u201391|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141006082219/http://www.edge-online.com/review/review-bayonetta/|archivedate=October 6, 2014|accessdate=2015-11-27}}</ref> ''[[GamesRadar]]''<nowiki/>'s Nathan Irvine also said that the game nailed \"the epic scale of everything\" that unfolded in front of the player and \"manner in which it's delivered\", believed it was better than ''[[God of War Collection]]'', ''[[Devil May Cry 4]]'', and ''[[Ninja Gaiden Sigma 2]]'', and praised its \"superb action\" and humor. However, he said the only time its plot made sense was \"right at the end\", and complained about some of the game's \"insanely frustrating\" [[Quick Time Event|Quick Time Events]] (QTEs).<ref name=\"gamesradar-review2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gamesradar.com/xbox360/bayonetta/review/bayonetta/a-2009122215515698373414/g-2008051422316843088|title=Bayonetta Review|last=Irvine|first=Nathan|date=December 22, 2009|website=[[GamesRadar]] (Future plc)|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101226112442/http://www.gamesradar.com/xbox360/bayonetta/review/bayonetta/a-2009122215515698373414/g-2008051422316843088|archive-date=December 26, 2010|accessdate=December 23, 2009}}  (The review is for the 360 version, but GamesRadar [http://www.gamesradar.com/ps3/bayonetta/review/bayonetta/a-2009122114251985044/g-2008051422211399009 uses the same score and text for the PS3 port] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110615190710/http://www.gamesradar.com/ps3/bayonetta/review/bayonetta/a-2009122114251985044/g-2008051422211399009|date=2011-06-15}}.)</ref> Staff at ''[[GameSpot]]'' UK labelled the \"Witch Time\" mechanic a \"cool move\" and one of the two [[boss (video gaming)|boss]] battles they fought were \"pretty intense\", and said that it was \"easy to see the similarities\" between the game and ''Devil May Cry''.<ref name=\"gamespot-handson\" /> They also opined that \"rampant violence and sexism\" was common in the game.<ref name=\"gamespot-handson\" /> One comment in regards to the third person perspective was from IGN UK's Martin Robinson, who said that it wasn't \"''Devil May Cry'', ''[[Ninja Gaiden (2004 video game)|Ninja Gaiden]]'' or ''[[God of War (franchise)|God of War]]''\" that served as the game's best point of reference but rather \"''[[Super Mario Galaxy]]''\" - he commented on how ''Bayonetta,'' like ''Galaxy'', \"loves to tinker with the player's sense of perspective\".<ref name=\"wired-handson\" /> Daniel Feit found the game's commands easy to learn and perform, but criticized the camera for focusing \"on her and the wall\" instead of  \"the enemies cornering her\" and felt that some of her \"Wicked Weave\" attacks could \"also obscure the action\".<ref name=\"ignuk-360review2\">{{cite web|url=http://xbox360.ign.com/articles/105/1057055p1.html|title=Bayonetta UK Review (Xbox 360)|last=Robinson|first=Martin|date=December 22, 2009|publisher=IGN|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091226040038/http://xbox360.ign.com/articles/105/1057055p1.html|archivedate=26 December 2009 <!--DASHBot-->|accessdate=December 23, 2009}}</ref> Clements labelled its voice work \"a bit campy but still extremely enjoyable\", but said the game's plot was \"all over the place\" and wasn't as well told as \"game stories like ''[[Mass Effect]]'' and ''[[Uncharted]]''\".<ref name=\"ign-ps3review2\" /><ref name=\"ign-360review2\">{{cite web|url=http://xbox360.ign.com/articles/105/1056885p1.html|title=Bayonetta Review (Xbox 360)|last=Clements|first=Ryan|date=December 22, 2009|publisher=IGN|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091225193442/http://xbox360.ign.com/articles/105/1056885p1.html|archivedate=25 December 2009 <!--DASHBot-->|accessdate=December 22, 2009}}</ref> However, ''[[Gamearena]]'' felt that the gameplay would not appeal to many, commenting that ''Devil May Cry'' was seen by many to be \"too campy and over-the-top\" and ''Bayonetta'' made it look \"monochrome\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamearena.com.au/xbox360/games/title/bayonetta/reviews.php/bayonetta|title=BigPond GameArena - Bayonetta Reviews|date=January 7, 2010|publisher=Gamearena.com.au|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111001123521/http://www.gamearena.com.au/xbox360/games/title/bayonetta/reviews.php/bayonetta|archivedate=October 1, 2011|accessdate=January 12, 2010}}</ref> \n\nThe game in general was praised by ''[[Eurogamer]]'', who commented that the game exemplified \"so much of what commentators claim has died in the Japanese game industry\" and said that ''Bayonetta'' was a \"blast of creative brilliance, both technically accomplished, strategically deep and infused with rare imagination\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/bayonetta-import-review?page=2|title=Bayonetta Review \u2022 Page \u2022 Reviews \u2022 Xbox 360 \u2022|last=Parkin|first=Simon|date=November 18, 2009|website=Eurogamer|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121002061239/http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/bayonetta-import-review?page=2|archive-date=October 2, 2012|accessdate=June 24, 2012}}</ref> But the [[Associated Press]] review opined that the game ''\"''would have blown [them] away 15 years ago\" and felt that ''Bayonetta'' didn't give the player \"anything to do except fight\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sandiegouniontribune.com/news/2010/jan/06/review-segas-bayonetta-flamboyant-but-shallow/|title=Review: Sega's 'Bayonetta' flamboyant but shallow|last=Keston|first=Lou|date=2010-01-06|work=Associated Press|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160513164400/http://www.sandiegouniontribune.com/news/2010/jan/06/review-segas-bayonetta-flamboyant-but-shallow/|archive-date=2016-05-13|accessdate=2016-04-23}}</ref>\n\nDaan Koopman at Nintendo World Report, reviewing the [[Wii U]] version, rated the game an 8/10, stating that ''Bayonetta'' was \"still a glorious action game\" and that \"time has not really changed that one bit\". He also praised the addition of the Nintendo-themed costumes, for their humor and functions.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nintendoworldreport.com/review/38566/bayonetta-review|title=Bayonetta Review - Review|work=Nintendo World Report|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141024085123/http://www.nintendoworldreport.com/review/38566/bayonetta-review|archive-date=October 24, 2014|accessdate=October 30, 2014}}</ref>\n\nIGN UK announced that ''Bayonetta'' was their pick for the 2010 [[Game of the Year]] (GOTY).<ref name=\"GOTY2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.magx01.blogspot.com/2010/12/ign-uk-weekend-initiative-top-ten-games.html|title=IGN UK Weekend Initiative Top Ten Games of 2010|date=December 10, 2010|publisher=Thoughtful Gamers|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110708051842/http://www.magx01.blogspot.com/2010/12/ign-uk-weekend-initiative-top-ten-games.html|archive-date=July 8, 2011|accessdate=2010-12-11}}</ref>\n\nThe game was nominated for the Freedom Tower Award for Best Remake as part of the ''Bayonetta 1 and Bayonetta 2 Collection'' at the New York Game Awards.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://screenrant.com/2018-new-york-game-awards-nominees/|title=2018 New York Game Awards Nominees Revealed|last=Keyes|first=Rob|date=January 3, 2019|work=[[Screen Rant]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190105150909/https://screenrant.com/2018-new-york-game-awards-nominees/|archive-date=January 5, 2019|accessdate=January 9, 2019}}</ref>\n\n''Bayonetta'' was one of twelve games to receive a 2009 Japan Game Awards \"Future Division\" award at the 2009 Tokyo Game Show.<ref name=\"cesa-futuredivision\">{{cite web |url=http://awards.cesa.or.jp/en/prize/prize_02.html |title=Future Division Awarded Games |publisher=[[Computer Entertainment Supplier's Association]] |accessdate=December 23, 2009 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091019085218/http://awards.cesa.or.jp/en/prize/prize_02.html |archivedate=October 19, 2009 }}</ref><ref name=\"pg-tgs2009award\">{{cite web |last=Kamiya |first=Hideki |url=http://platinumgames.com/2009/11/15/tokyo-game-show/ |title=Tokyo Game Show |publisher=PlatinumGames |date=November 15, 2009 |accessdate=December 23, 2009 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100119032353/http://platinumgames.com/2009/11/15/tokyo-game-show/ |archivedate=January 19, 2010 |url-status = dead }}</ref><ref name=\"sega-tgs2009award\">{{cite web |url=http://blog.bayonetta.jp/archives/988 |script-title=ja:\u5927\u91cf\u306b\u3054\u5831\u544a |publisher=Sega |language=Japanese |date=October 13, 2009 |accessdate=December 23, 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091016052655/http://blog.bayonetta.jp/archives/988 |archive-date=October 16, 2009 |url-status = live }}</ref>\n\n=== Sales figures ===\nSinobi, a Japanese blog known for its early sales data, reported that ''Bayonetta'' sold 138,000 copies\u201493,000 for the PS3 and 45,000 for the 360\u2014on its day of release in the country.<ref name=\"andriasang-firstsales\">{{cite web |last=Gantayat |first=Anoop |url=http://www.andriasang.com/e/blog/2009/10/30/bayonetta_first_day_sales/ |title=Xbox 360 VS PS3 in First Day Bayonetta Sales |publisher=andriasang.com |date=October 30, 2009 |accessdate=October 31, 2009 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091106000201/http://www.andriasang.com/e/blog/2009/10/30/bayonetta_first_day_sales/ |archivedate=6 November 2009 |url-status = dead }}</ref> [[Media Create]] reported the PS3 version sold 135,242 copies and was the top-selling game during its week of release there, while the 360 version sold 64,325 copies and charted at number seven.<ref name=\"mediacreate-firstweek\">{{cite web |url=http://www.m-create.com/ranking/ |title=This Week's Ranking (\u4eca\u9031\u306e\u30e9\u30f3\u30ad\u30f3\u30b0) |publisher=[[Media Create]] |language=Japanese |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100103160504/http://m-create.com/ranking/ |archivedate=January 3, 2010 |accessdate=December 22, 2009 |url-status = dead }}</ref><ref name=\"gamasutra-firstweek\">{{cite web|last=Graft |first=Kris |url=http://www.gamasutra.com/php-bin/news_index.php?story=25963 |title=Japanese Software: Bayonetta For PS3 Leads Charts, Pokemon Dethroned |website=[[Gamasutra]] |date=November 5, 2009 |accessdate=November 5, 2009 | archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20091108195023/http://www.gamasutra.com/php-bin/news_index.php?story=25963| archivedate= 8 November 2009 <!--DASHBot-->|url-status = live}}</ref>  Phil Elliott of [[GamesIndustry.biz]] called the 360 version's lower sales figures \"a very strong performance for the Microsoft platform, relative to installed base\".<ref name=\"gamesindustry-firstweek\">{{cite web|last=Elliott |first=Phil |url=http://www.gamesindustry.biz/articles/bayonetta-bosses-japanese-software-chart |title=Bayonetta bosses Japanese software chart |website=Eurogamer |date=November 6, 2009 |accessdate=December 22, 2009 | archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100121095907/http://www.gamesindustry.biz/articles/bayonetta-bosses-japanese-software-chart| archivedate= 21 January 2010 <!--DASHBot-->|url-status = live}}</ref>  The two releases fell to number eight and number 15 respectively the following week.<ref name=\"kotaku-secondweek\">{{cite web|last=McWhertor |first=Michael |title=Konami Kicks Bayonetta Off Top Of Japan's Game Charts |url=http://kotaku.com/5403328/konami-kicks-bayonetta-off-top-of-japans-game-charts |website=Kotaku |date=November 12, 2009 |accessdate=November 12, 2009 | archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20091114095407/http://kotaku.com/5403328/konami-kicks-bayonetta-off-top-of-japans-game-charts| archivedate= 14 November 2009 <!--DASHBot-->|url-status = live}}</ref> By March 31, 2010, ''Bayonetta'' sold 1.35 million units worldwide.<ref name=\"figures\">{{cite web|url=http://www.segasammy.co.jp/english/pdf/release/20100514_hosoku_e_final.pdf#page=5|title=Appendix of Consolidated Financial Statements|accessdate=April 1, 2011|publisher=[[Sega Sammy Holdings]]|date=May 14, 2010|page=5|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111003122820/http://www.segasammy.co.jp/english/pdf/release/20100514_hosoku_e_final.pdf#page=5|archive-date=October 3, 2011|url-status = live}}</ref> In retrospective, Platinum's president Tatsuya Minami stated ''Bayonetta'' was their best-selling title but commented the sales did not beat their expectations.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2013-04-17-platinum-games-president-rates-its-sales-as-a-c-or-even-a-d|title=PlatinumGames president rates its sales as a \"C or even a D.\"|accessdate=June 22, 2013|website=[[Eurogamer]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303224030/http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2013-04-17-platinum-games-president-rates-its-sales-as-a-c-or-even-a-d|archive-date=March 3, 2016|url-status = live}}</ref>\n\nAbout a month after its release on [[Microsoft Windows]], Sega Europe's Vice President of Publishing John Clark said that the Windows version had sold more than 170,000 units, and that Sega was \"really happy\" on this performance.<ref>\n{{Cite web | url = https://www.destructoid.com/bayonetta-pc-port-clears-170-000-sales-437840.phtml | title = Bayonetta PC port clears 170,000 sales | first = Ray | last = Porreca | date = May 24, 2017 | accessdate = May 24, 2017 | work = [[Destructoid]] | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20170603081610/https://www.destructoid.com/bayonetta-pc-port-clears-170-000-sales-437840.phtml | archive-date = June 3, 2017 |url-status = live }}\n</ref>\n\n==Sequels==\n{{Main|Bayonetta 2}}\n\nA sequel, ''Bayonetta 2'', was announced in September 2012 as a [[Wii U]] title to be published by [[Nintendo]]. The game, released in Japan in September 2014 and released in North America and Europe in December 2014, features a port of the original ''Bayonetta'', which adds costumes based on Nintendo properties including ''[[Super Mario]]'', ''[[The Legend of Zelda]]'', ''[[Star Fox]]'' and ''[[Metroid]]'', as well as touch screen controls and dual audio tracks.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.polygon.com/2014/6/10/5795904/bayonetta-2-release-date-wii-u-bayonetta-remake |title=Bayonetta 2 coming to Wii U this October, includes original Bayonetta |website=Polygon |date= |accessdate=2014-08-19 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140714114339/http://www.polygon.com/2014/6/10/5795904/bayonetta-2-release-date-wii-u-bayonetta-remake |archive-date=2014-07-14 |url-status = live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.siliconera.com/2014/06/11/bayonetta-wii-u-60fps-tv-play-dual-audio/ |title=Bayonetta On Wii U: 60fps, Off-TV Play, Dual Audio |website=Siliconera |date=June 11, 2014 |accessdate=August 19, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140821121206/http://www.siliconera.com/2014/06/11/bayonetta-wii-u-60fps-tv-play-dual-audio/ |archive-date=August 21, 2014 |url-status = live }}</ref>\n\nAnother sequel, ''Bayonetta 3'', was announced during [[The Game Awards 2017]] in December as a [[Nintendo Switch]] title, alongside the announcement of Switch ports for the previous two games.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.polygon.com/2017/12/7/16749668/bayonetta-3-trailer-nintendo-switch-platinum-games-tga-2017 | title = Nintendo announces Bayonetta 3 as a Switch exclusive | first = Ben | last = Kuchera | date = December 7, 2017 | accessdate = December 8, 2017 | work = [[Polygon (website)|Polygon]] | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20171208231540/https://www.polygon.com/2017/12/7/16749668/bayonetta-3-trailer-nintendo-switch-platinum-games-tga-2017 | archive-date = December 8, 2017 |url-status = live }}</ref> \n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n; General\n{{Refbegin}}\n* {{cite web |last=Mielke |first=James |url=http://www.1up.com/do/previewPage?cId=3169684 |archive-url=https://archive.today/20120629234941/http://www.1up.com/do/previewPage?cId=3169684 |url-status = dead|archive-date=June 29, 2012 |title=Bayonetta (PS3): Previews: In the September EGM, we laid out \"25 Things You Need To Know About Bayonetta.\" Now, we're happy to unveil the full-length interview behind that story. |website=[[1UP.com]] |date=August 29, 2008 |accessdate=October 27, 2009 |ref=harv }}\n{{Refend}}\n; Specific\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikiquote}}\n* {{Official website|http://www.sega.com/platinumgames/bayonetta/}}\n* {{mobygames|id=/Bayonetta}}\n{{Hideki Kamiya}}\n{{PlatinumGames}}\n{{Divine Comedy navbox}}\n\n[[Category:2009 video games]]\n[[Category:Action video games]]\n[[Category:Bayonetta]]\n[[Category:Fantasy video games]]\n[[Category:Hack and slash games]]\n[[Category:Nex Entertainment games]]\n[[Category:Nintendo games]]\n[[Category:Nintendo Switch eShop games]]\n[[Category:Nintendo Switch games]]\n[[Category:PlatinumGames games]]\n[[Category:PlayStation 3 games]]\n[[Category:PlayStation 4 games]]\n[[Category:PlayStation 4 Pro enhanced games]]\n[[Category:Purgatory in fiction]]\n[[Category:Sega beat 'em ups]]\n[[Category:Sega video games]]\n[[Category:Single-player video games]]\n[[Category:Third-person shooters]]\n[[Category:Video games about angels]]\n[[Category:Video games about shapeshifting]]\n[[Category:Video games about time travel]]\n[[Category:Video games developed in Japan]]\n[[Category:Video games directed by Hideki Kamiya]]\n[[Category:Video games featuring female protagonists]]\n[[Category:Video games set in Europe]]\n[[Category:Wii U eShop games]]\n[[Category:Wii U games]]\n[[Category:Windows games]]\n[[Category:Witchcraft in video games]]\n[[Category:Xbox 360 games]]\n[[Category:Xbox One games]]\n[[Category:Xbox One X enhanced games]]\n", "text_old": "{{about|the video game|the character|Bayonetta (character)}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{short description|2009 video game}}\n{{Infobox video game\n| title = Bayonetta\n| image = Bayonetta box artwork.png\n| caption = Cover art used in Japan for the original release and internationally for the Wii U release\n| developer = [[PlatinumGames]]{{efn|[[PlayStation 3]] version developed by [[Nex Entertainment]]; [[Wii U]] version developed by Bee Tribe; additional work for [[Microsoft Windows]] by Little Stone Software}}\n| publisher = {{ubl|[[Sega]]{{efn|[[PlayStation 3]], [[Xbox 360]], [[Microsoft Windows]], [[PlayStation 4]], [[Xbox One]]}}|[[Nintendo]]{{efn|[[Wii U]], [[Nintendo Switch]]}}}}\n| director = [[Hideki Kamiya]]\n| producer = {{collapsible list|titlestyle=font-weight:normal;font-size:normal;background:transparent;text-align:left|title=Yusuke Hashimoto|Akiko Kuroda (Wii U)|Hitoshi Yamagami (Wii U)|Atsushi Kurooka (PC)}}\n| designer = {{ubl|Hiroshi Shibata|Masaaki Yamada}}\n| artist = Mari Shimazaki\n| writer = Hideki Kamiya\n| composer = {{collapsible list|title=List of composers|[[Norihiko Hibino]]|[[Takahiro Izutani]]|Masami Ueda|Hiroshi Yamaguchi|Rei Kondoh|Takayasu Sodeoka|Erina Niwa|Yoshitaka Suzuki|Naoto Tanaka}}\n| series = \n| platforms = [[PlayStation 3]], [[Xbox 360]], {{nowrap|[[Wii U]]}}, [[Microsoft Windows]], [[Nintendo Switch]], {{nowrap|[[PlayStation 4]]}}, [[Xbox One]]\n| released = {{collapsible list|titlestyle=font-weight:normal;font-size:normal;background:transparent;text-align:left|title=October 29, 2009|'''PlayStation 3, Xbox 360'''{{vgrelease|JP|October 29, 2009|NA|January 5, 2010|AU|January 7, 2010|EU|January 8, 2010}}'''Wii U'''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://e3.nintendo.com/games/wiiu/bayonetta/ |title=Bayonetta for Wii U - Nintendo @ E3 |publisher=E3.nintendo.com |date= |accessdate=August 19, 2014 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140714162058/http://e3.nintendo.com/games/wiiu/bayonetta/ |archivedate=July 14, 2014 }}</ref>{{vgrelease|JP|September 20, 2014|[[North America|NA]]/[[Europe|EU]]|October 24, 2014|AU|October 25, 2014}}'''Microsoft Windows'''{{vgrelease|WW|April 11, 2017}}'''Nintendo Switch'''{{vgrelease|WW|February 16, 2018<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.polygon.com/2017/12/7/16750044/bayonetta-nintendo-switch-date-trailer-tga-2017|title=Bayonetta 1 + 2 are heading to Nintendo Switch|author=Polygon|date=December 7, 2017|access-date=December 8, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171208111628/https://www.polygon.com/2017/12/7/16750044/bayonetta-nintendo-switch-date-trailer-tga-2017|archive-date=December 8, 2017|url-status = live}}</ref>|JP|February 17, 2018}}'''PlayStation 4, Xbox One'''{{vgrelease|WW|February 18, 2020}}}}\n| genre = [[Action game|Action]], [[hack and slash]]\n| modes = [[Single-player]]\n}}\n{{Nihongo foot|'''''Bayonetta'''''|\u30d9\u30e8\u30cd\u30c3\u30bf|Beyonetta|lead=yes|group=lower-alpha}} is an [[action-adventure]] [[hack and slash]] video game developed by [[PlatinumGames]] and published by [[Sega]]. The game was originally released for [[Xbox 360]] and [[PlayStation 3]] in Japan in October 2009, and in North America and Europe in January 2010. The game was later released on the [[Wii U]] alongside its sequel, ''[[Bayonetta 2]]'', releasing in September 2014 in Japan and worldwide the following month - the two games were later released worldwide on the [[Nintendo Switch]] in February 2018. An enhanced port for [[Microsoft Windows]] was released in April 2017 with [[4K resolution|4K]] support. A remastered version of ''Bayonetta'' as well as another PlatinumGames title, [[Vanquish (video game)|''Vanquish'']], was released for [[PlayStation 4]] and [[Xbox One]] on February 18, 2020, as part of a ''Bayonetta & Vanquish 10th Anniversary Bundle'' compilation.<ref name=\"IGN cites 10th anniversary release\" />\n\n''Bayonetta'' takes place in Vigrid, a fictional city in Europe. The game stars [[Bayonetta (character)|the eponymous character]], a witch who is capable of shapeshifting and using various firearms. She possesses magical attacks, and she can use her hair to summon demons to dispatch her foes. The game features a rating system, which gives players a grade based on their performance, and a combat system that is similar to the ''[[Devil May Cry]]'' series, also created by ''Bayonetta'' creator [[Hideki Kamiya]].\n\nDevelopment of the game was started in January 2007, with Hideki Kamiya being the game's director. According to Kamiya, the game was completely original, though he drew some inspirations from [[Scandinavian mythology]], and played ''[[Devil May Cry 4]]'' for reference. The game's theme is \"sexiness\" and \"partial nudity\", and that the characters were designed to be \"fashionable\". Kamiya and artist Mari Shimazaki spent more than a year to create Bayonetta's design. Several demos were released for the game prior to its launch. ''Bayonetta'' was the third project released by [[PlatinumGames]], which was founded by former [[Clover Studio]] employees. Upon release, the game received generally positive reviews. The game was praised for its combat, presentation and soundtrack, but drew criticism for its story and quick time events. The game was nominated for and won several end-of-the-year accolades, and had sold over a million units worldwide by 2010. An [[anime]] film adaptation of the game by [[Gonzo (company)|Gonzo]], titled ''[[Bayonetta: Bloody Fate]]'', was released in Japan in November 2013. A third game, ''Bayonetta 3'', is in development for the Switch.\n\n==Gameplay==\n[[File:Bayonetta kick.jpg|thumb|left|''Bayonetta'' gameplay screenshot, demonstrating one of the available \"Wicked Weave\" attacks.|alt=Screenshot of a woman with revealing attire in an outdoor setting.  Above her is a dark, giant leg, composed of and attached to her hair and attacking a staff-wielding enemy to the left of her. Behind them is a fountain and various buildings. In each corner (except the bottom left) are game scores and indicators.]]\n\n''Bayonetta'' is a single-player, [[Third-person view|third-person]] 3D [[action game]]. Its combat system is similar to that of director Hideki Kamiya's previous title, ''[[Devil May Cry (video game)|Devil May Cry]]''.<ref name=\"gi-marchiafava\">{{cite web |last=Marchiafava |first=Jeff |url=http://gameinformer.com/games/bayonetta/b/ps3/archive/2009/09/29/preview.aspx |title=Bayonetta |work=[[Game Informer]] |publisher=[[GameStop]] |date=September 29, 2009 |accessdate=October 15, 2009 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091105041836/http://gameinformer.com/games/bayonetta/b/ps3/archive/2009/09/29/preview.aspx |archivedate=2009-11-05 |url-status = dead }}</ref> The player controls a witch named [[Bayonetta (character)|Bayonetta]]. By sing melee and long ranged attacks, complex combo strings, and multiple weapons, the game encourages to explore ways to dispatch angelic enemies with as much flair as possible. Special commands or actions are woven into events, finishes, executions, and unique \"Torture Attacks\" in which Bayonetta summons a variety of devices to deal devastating blows to her enemies. Such devices range from [[chainsaw]]s to [[iron maiden (torture)|iron maiden]]s.<ref name=\"gamespot-handson\">{{cite web |last=Mc Shea |first=Tom |url=http://uk.gamespot.com/ps3/action/bayonetta/news.html?sid=6211066&mode=previews |title=Bayonetta Hands-On |website=GameSpot UK |date=June 3, 2009 |accessdate=October 10, 2009 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20130123184826/http://uk.gamespot.com/ps3/action/bayonetta/news.html?sid=6211066&mode=previews |archivedate=January 23, 2013 }}</ref> Bayonetta has unique but limited abilities that her enemies do not possess, such as \"Witch Time\", which activates when the player makes a well-timed dodge to an attack. This temporarily slows time to allow Bayonetta to inflict massive amounts of counter damage before the enemies can react.<ref>{{cite web |title=Bayonetta Demo Impressions |last=Tong |first=Sophia |url=http://uk.gamespot.com/ps3/action/bayonetta/news.html?sid=6211091&mode=previews |date=June 3, 2009  |website=GameSpot UK |accessdate=September 10, 2009 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20120720171523/http://uk.gamespot.com/ps3/action/bayonetta/news.html?sid=6211091&mode=previews |archivedate=July 20, 2012 }}</ref>\n\nThe player can double jump for extra height, perform evasive backflips, and destroy background objects and doors. Camera views can be rotated, enemy targets can be locked on, and weapons can be switched during play.<ref name=\"1up-handson\">{{cite web |last=Leone |first=Matt |url=http://www.1up.com/do/previewPage?cId=3174471 |title=Bayonetta (PS3): Previews: We've got the first ever hands-on preview of the next big action game from the director of Resident Evil 2, Devil May Cry, Viewtiful Joe, and Okami. |website=1UP.com |date=June 1, 2009 |accessdate=October 11, 2009 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120109181429/http://www.1up.com/previews/bayonetta |archivedate=January 9, 2012 }}</ref> With unlockable transformations, the player can make Bayonetta become a panther or one of various other living creatures to enhance her abilities.<ref name=\"1up-transforms\">{{cite web |last=Leone |first=Matt |url=http://www.1up.com/do/previewPage?cId=3174402 |title=Bayonetta (PS3): Previews: Learn new details about the panther, and a few hints about other yet-to-be-revealed transformations. |website=1UP.com |date=May 27, 2009 |accessdate=October 15, 2009 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120730202517/http://www.1up.com/previews/bayonetta_2 |archivedate=July 30, 2012 }}</ref> Lollipops can be used to [[health (gaming)|heal]] her, replenish her magic, induce invincibility or increase her strength, although using these items, as well as dying, lowers the score for that chapter.<ref name=\"ign-ps3review\">{{cite web|last=Clements |first=Ryan |url=http://ps3.ign.com/articles/105/1057012p1.html |title=Bayonetta Review (PlayStation 3) |publisher=IGN |date=December 22, 2009 |accessdate=December 22, 2009 | archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20091226035445/http://ps3.ign.com/articles/105/1057012p1.html| archivedate= 26 December 2009 <!--DASHBot-->|url-status = live}}</ref> By finding various component items, the player can combine them into new items. Many enemies and objects drop halos when destroyed, which the player can use to buy items, techniques and weapon upgrades.<ref name=\"ign-progress\">{{cite web |last=Shea |first=Cam |url=http://ps3.ign.com/articles/964/964193p1.html |title=Bayonetta Progress Report |publisher=IGN |date=March 19, 2009 |accessdate=October 10, 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090322040007/http://ps3.ign.com/articles/964/964193p1.html |archive-date=March 22, 2009 |url-status = live }}</ref><ref name=\"1up-handson\" /> The player can use enemy weapons, either to directly attack or as props for movement. Bayonetta's strongest attacks allow her to summon parts of Madama Butterfly and other demons with her hair.<ref name=\"ign-progress\" /> Bayonetta starts the game with four guns, two in her hands, two on her feet. By finding golden [[LP album]]s, some of which are in multiple pieces, players can earn new weapons, such as shotguns, a katana and a whip. These can be customized to Bayonetta's arms and legs in various combinations.\n\nThe game consists of multiple chapters, each consisting of several verses. Depending on how well the player performs, they are given one of the following medals at the end of the verse; Stone, Bronze, Silver, Gold, Platinum and Pure Platinum, similar to the rating system of ''[[Viewtiful Joe]]''. There are some medals that are earned off the beaten path, such as special areas with set challenges. At the end of the chapter, a final score and an award are given depending on the type of medals achieved, with the score being deducted for any items used and deaths occurred. In between chapters there is a minigame called ''Angel Attack'', in which players use Arcade Bullets found in the main levels to shoot at angels and earn points. These points can be traded in for items, with any leftover points exchanged for halos.\n\n==Plot==\n\n===Setting and characters===\n''Bayonetta'' takes place in Vigrid, a fictional city in Europe.<ref name=\"ign-progress\"/> The [[Bayonetta (character)|title character]] (voiced by Hellena Taylor)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://hellenataylor.com/reel_voice.html |title=Hellena Taylor |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100119162428/http://hellenataylor.com/reel_voice.html |archivedate=2010-01-19 }}</ref> is a witch who [[shapeshifting|shapeshifts]] and uses various firearms, along with magical attacks she performs with her hair by summoning demons to dispatch her foes. She awakens after a 500-year sleep<ref name=\"gamespot-updated\">{{cite web|last=Anderson |first=Luke |url=http://www.gamespot.com/ps3/action/bayonetta/news.html?sid=6216007&mode=previews |title=Bayonetta Updated Impressions |website=GameSpot |date=August 22, 2009 |accessdate=October 16, 2009 | archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20091006111403/http://www.gamespot.com/ps3/action/bayonetta/news.html?sid=6216007&mode=previews| archivedate= 6 October 2009 <!--DASHBot-->|url-status = live}}</ref> and finds herself in an unfamiliar area with no memories of who or what she is. Over time, she begins to remember what caused her current predicament. 500 years before the incident that caused Bayonetta's memory loss, there were two factions preserving the balance between darkness and light in the world: the Umbra Witches, who are followers of darkness, and their counterparts, the Lumen Sages, who are followers of light. The factions shared two distinct treasures, the 'Eyes of the World' (separately named the 'Left Eye' and the 'Right Eye') which they used to oversee the just passage of time. Both factions mysteriously disappeared from Vigrid under unknown circumstances.<ref>{{cite video |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=qqgtpTkCQ3Q |title=TGS 09: Bayonetta Trailer |publisher=IGN |via=[[YouTube]] |format=Adobe Flash |date=September 24, 2009 |accessdate=December 23, 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140129123221/http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=qqgtpTkCQ3Q |archive-date=January 29, 2014 |url-status = live }}</ref> Bayonetta has an ornate piece of jewelry which contains a small red gem, and believes this gem is the Left Eye of the World. While searching for the Right Eye, she occasionally receives flashbacks that make her remember what happened.\n\nA male character known as {{Nihongo|Luka|\u30eb\u30ab}} (voiced by [[Yuri Lowenthal]]<ref name=\"kokugamer-review\">{{cite web|last=H |first=Maiku |url=http://kokugamer.com/2010/01/08/bayonetta-reviewxbox-360/ |title=Bayonetta Review |publisher=Koku Gamer |date=January 8, 2010 |accessdate=June 6, 2010 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100114034955/http://kokugamer.com/2010/01/08/bayonetta-reviewxbox-360/ |archivedate=January 14, 2010 }}</ref>) had met Bayonetta as a child.<ref name=\"gamespot-updated\" /><ref name=\"bayo-chars\">{{cite web |url=http://bayonetta.jp/main.html |title=<nowiki>Bayonetta\u2014\u30d9\u30e8\u30cd\u30c3\u30bf | Official Website\u2014Character</nowiki> |publisher=Sega |format=[[Adobe Flash]] |year=2008 |accessdate=October 24, 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100301112640/http://bayonetta.jp/main.html |archive-date=March 1, 2010 |url-status = live }}</ref> Other characters include Bayonetta's rival and fellow Umbra Witch {{Nihongo|Jeanne|\u30b8\u30e3\u30f3\u30cc|Jannu}} (voiced by [[Grey DeLisle]]<ref name=\"PlatinumGames1\">[{{cite web|url=http://platinumgames.com/2013/02/06/bayonetta-developer-commentary-part-56/ |title=Bayonetta Developer Commentary Part 56] |publisher=PlatinumGames |accessdate=October 30, 2014 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130616231758/http://platinumgames.com/2013/02/06/bayonetta-developer-commentary-part-56/ |archivedate=June 16, 2013  }}</ref>), who wields four guns like Bayonetta; {{Nihongo|Rodin|\u30ed\u30c0\u30f3|Rodan}} (voiced by [[Dave Fennoy]]<ref name=\"PlatinumGames1\"/>), the owner of a bar called the Gates Of Hell where Bayonetta can buy various weapons and items; an informant named {{Nihongo|Enzo|\u30a8\u30f3\u30c4\u30a9|Entso}} (voiced by [[Chick Vennera]]<ref name=\"PlatinumGames1\"/>) who looks and sounds similar to actor [[Joe Pesci]], and provides comic relief; a young girl named {{Nihongo|Cereza|\u30bb\u30ec\u30c3\u30b5|Seressa}} (voiced by Joy Jillian<ref>{{cite podcast|url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/anncast/2014-10-20/.80139|title=ANNCast 203: Klein Times|publisher=Anime News Network|date=October 20, 2014|access-date=October 14, 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171014182708/http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/anncast/2014-10-20/.80139|archivedate=October 14, 2017|url-status = live}}</ref>) whom Bayonetta meets early in the game; and the main antagonist {{Nihongo|Balder|\u30d0\u30eb\u30c9\u30eb|Barudoru}} (voiced by Grant Albrecht<ref name=\"PlatinumGames1\"/>).<ref name=\"bayo-chars\" />\n\nThe realms Bayonetta inhabits are the game's different settings, which borrow from Dante's ''[[Divine Comedy]]'': [[Paradiso (Dante)|Paradiso]] (heaven), which generally takes the form of a heavenly yellow or golden valley or palace and is the home of the \"Angel\" enemies she faces; [[Purgatorio]] (purgatory), a metarealm that functions as an \"in between\" for metaphysical beings and stands alongside yet outside of the plane humans exist on (all beings in and outside of Purgatorio take on a transparent, watery appearance); [[Inferno (Dante)|Inferno]] (hell), which is the game's realm that contains infernal demons of the sort that Bayonetta herself occasionally summons with her Witch powers (usually by using her hair as a conduit). The diaries written by Luka's father mention that the Witches actually drew most of their power from both the demons in Inferno, and The Human World, otherwise known as Chaos, the realm regular humans live in.\n\n===Story===\nIn the present day, an informant named Enzo has joined up with Bayonetta, a witch who was revived twenty years ago from the bottom of a lake and has no memories of her past. Owning one-half of the \"Eyes of the World,\" Bayonetta leaves for Vigrid when Enzo informs her of rumors the other half is there.\n\nAfterward, Bayonetta confronts another Umbra Witch named Jeanne, as well as a young man named Luka; the former seemingly has ties to Bayonetta's past, while the latter blames Bayonetta for his father's death. Bayonetta then battles through Vigrid before encountering Fortitudo, one of the four [[Cardinal Virtues]], and defeats him.\n\nMaking her way through the Crescent and Sunrise Valleys, Bayonetta finds Jeanne conversing with [[Temperance (virtue)|Temperantia]], the second of the Cardinal Virtues; after defeating Jeanne, she then meets a lost child named Cereza. Much to Bayonetta's frustration, the child believes she's her mother and follows her; after eventually returning to the human world, Bayonetta leaves Cereza with Luka and confronts Temperantia, whom she defeats. Continuing her search for the Right Eye, Bayonetta follows Luka and Cereza down Prominence Bridge in an attempt to reach the island known as Isla del Sol; she is attacked by [[Justice (virtue)|Iustitia]], the third Cardinal Virtue, and defeats him.\n\nThe trio board a [[Valkyrie]] jet headed for Isla del Sol, only for Cereza to become lost. After finding her and fighting Jeanne again, [[Prudence|Sapientia]], the final Cardinal Virtue, attacks and downs the jet, and Bayonetta defeats him. The three then head for Isla del Sol by helicopter and then by a missile. When they reach the island, Bayonetta is confronted again by Jeanne, who explains Bayonetta was a child born from an Umbra Witch and a Lumen Sage, which was forbidden and resulted in Bayonetta being ostracized. Bayonetta defeats Jeanne, who reveals the reason Bayonetta possesses the Left Eye is because she has accepted her fate. Bayonetta hands Jeanne the gem she had been carrying, making her remember she is Cereza, and that Jeanne was once her friend; it was Jeanne who sealed her away, giving Bayonetta the gem to protect her and the Left Eye. After Jeanne then sacrifices herself to save Bayonetta, she continues through the tower with Luka and Cereza.\n\nUpon reaching the top, Bayonetta finally meets Father Balder, the last of the Lumen Sages. Balder reveals he is Bayonetta's father, and that he plans to reunite the three universes by resurrecting Jubileus, the Creator; however, since Bayonetta could not remember her past, Cereza was sent back to her to help her remember, allowing Balder to use her as the Left Eye. After revealing he was responsible for the death of Luka's father, Balder throws Luka to his death, before fighting Bayonetta among rubble falling from the tower. Bayonetta ultimately manages to defeat Balder before saving a falling Luka and Cereza.\n\nAfter making a time portal to return her younger self home, Bayonetta returns to the present, only to collapse after regaining her memory; seemingly unharmed, Balder transports himself and the unconscious Bayonetta towards the statue on top of the tower, beginning the resurrection of Jubileus. As the statue launches into space, Jeanne reappears after earlier escaping both death and Balder's control narrowly. She ascends the launching statue on her motorcycle by riding along the surface; after reaching Bayonetta, she saves her, only for Jubileus to come alive and consume Balder. Jeanne floats away from the statue, leaving Bayonetta alone to fight the deity. Bayonetta eventually defeats Jubileus by summoning [[Queen of Sheba|Queen Sheba]], who punches the deity's soul into the sun. As the statue left behind by Jubileus plummets towards Earth, Jeanne is revealed to be alive, and after destroying the last of the Jubileus statue, Bayonetta and Jeanne end up in a free-fall towards Earth; after surviving the descent, the epilogue shows them continuing to battle against the angels.\n\n==Development==\n{{quotebox|...&nbsp;it's been eight years since [the first ''[[Devil May Cry (video game)|DMC]]''], so of course I wouldn't create a game that hadn't progressed from those days! Of course, if there hadn't have been ''DMC'', there wouldn't be ''Bayonetta'', which has evolved from ''DMC''.|source=[[Hideki Kamiya]], April 2009<ref name=\"gamespot-qanda\">{{cite web |last=Ramsay |first=Randolph |url=http://www.gamespot.com/articles/qanda-hideki-kamiya-on-bayonetta/1100-6207621/ |title=Q&A: Hideki Kamiya on Bayonetta |website=GameSpot |date=April 8, 2009 |accessdate=October 21, 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150203014102/http://www.gamespot.com/articles/qanda-hideki-kamiya-on-bayonetta/1100-6207621/ |archive-date=February 3, 2015 |url-status = live }}</ref>|width=40%|}}\n\n[[Hideki Kamiya]] directed development of ''Bayonetta'' at [[PlatinumGames]] since January 2007,<ref name=\"pg-designing\">{{cite web |last=Shimazaki |first=Mari |url=http://platinumgames.com/2009/04/17/designing-bayonetta/ |title=Designing Bayonetta |publisher=PlatinumGames |date=April 17, 2009 |accessdate=October 10, 2009 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090820163727/http://platinumgames.com/2009/04/17/designing-bayonetta/ |archivedate=August 20, 2009 }}</ref><ref name=\"1up-interview-devstart\">{{harvnb|Mielke|2008|pp=1\u20132}}. \"[1UP.com:] In June of this year, we trekked down to Osaka, Japan, to meet up with the latest incarnation of Hideki Kamiya's development group, PlatinumGames.&nbsp;... [Hideki Kamiya]: It's been about a year and a half since we started.\"</ref> and the game was \"more-or-less complete\" by October 21, 2009.<ref name=\"1up-wrappingup\">{{cite web |last=Gifford |first=Kevin |url=http://www.1up.com/do/newsStory?cId=3176587 |archive-url=https://archive.today/20130116040000/http://www.1up.com/do/newsStory?cId=3176587 |url-status = dead|archive-date=January 16, 2013 |title=Hideki Kamiya on Wrapping Up Bayonetta |website=1UP.com |date=October 21, 2009 |accessdate=October 27, 2009 }}</ref> The group developed for [[Microsoft]]'s [[Xbox 360]] game console, while [[Sega]] - with PlatinumGames' support - handed the task of [[porting]] the game to [[Sony Computer Entertainment|Sony]]'s [[PlayStation 3]] to [[Nex Entertainment]].<ref name=\"pg-harvest\">{{cite web |last=Minami |first=Tatsuya |url=http://platinumgames.com/2009/09/18/fall-harvest/ |title=Fall Harvest |publisher=PlatinumGames |date=September 18, 2009 |accessdate=October 10, 2009 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090924215021/http://platinumgames.com/2009/09/18/fall-harvest/ |archivedate=September 24, 2009 }}</ref> Kamiya had worked on previous games such as ''[[Devil May Cry (video game)|Devil May Cry]]'', ''[[Viewtiful Joe]]'', ''[[Resident Evil (1996 video game)|Resident Evil]]'' and [[Resident Evil 2|its sequel]], and as such, the game makes occasional references to these games, as well as other [[Clover Studio]] titles and various [[Sega]] franchises, such as a minigame inspired by ''[[Space Harrier]]''.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://content.usatoday.com/communities/gamehunters/post/2009/11/bad-hair-day-hands-on-with-bayonetta/1 | work=USA Today | title=Bad hair day: Hands-on with 'Bayonetta' | date=November 30, 2009 | access-date=January 14, 2010 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091203172311/http://content.usatoday.com/communities/gamehunters/post/2009/11/bad-hair-day-hands-on-with-bayonetta/1 | archive-date=December 3, 2009 |url-status = live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gamesradar.com/f/30-hidden-references-in-bayonetta/a-2010011493658559064 |title=30 'hidden' references in Bayonetta |last=Reparaz |first=Mikel |date=January 14, 2010 |work=GamesRadar UK |accessdate=November 8, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110615185748/http://www.gamesradar.com/f/30-hidden-references-in-bayonetta/a-2010011493658559064 |archive-date=June 15, 2011 |url-status = live }}</ref>\n\nMari Shimazaki designed the game's characters to be \"fashionable\", with \"subdued\" features.<ref name=\"pg-designing2\">{{cite web|last=Shimazaki |first=Mari |url=http://platinumgames.com/2009/06/26/designing-bayonetta-part-2-jeanne/ |title=Designing Bayonetta Part 2\u2014Jeanne |publisher=PlatinumGames |date=June 26, 2009 |accessdate=October 10, 2009 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100102211423/http://platinumgames.com/2009/06/26/designing-bayonetta-part-2-jeanne/ |archivedate=January 2, 2010 }}</ref> She designed the titular character to fulfill Kamiya's request for a modern, female witch that wears glasses and wields four guns,<ref name=\"pg-designing\" /> and the two settled on her original concept for the character despite her work \"over a year\" on other concepts.<ref name=\"gspy-design\">{{cite web |last=Villoria |first=Gerald |url=http://xbox360.gamespy.com/xbox-360/bayonetta/1013849p1.html |title=Designing Bayonetta |publisher=[[GameSpy]] |date=August 13, 2009 |accessdate=October 15, 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090817215803/http://xbox360.gamespy.com/xbox-360/bayonetta/1013849p1.html |archive-date=August 17, 2009 |url-status = live }}</ref> Bayonetta emerged as a long-haired, black-clothed witch with a [[beehive (hairstyle)|beehive hairdo]] (a modern representation of the traditional [[pointy hat]]) and glasses (which Kamiya pushed for,&nbsp;to \"differentiate Bayonetta from other female characters\" and to \"give her a sense of mystery and intelligence\").<ref name=\"pg-designing\" /> Conversely, Shimazaki \"didn't require a huge amount of effort\" to design Bayonetta's short-haired, red-clothed rival Jeanne, who merely wears her glasses on her head above her eyes. She added plumes to Jeanne's handguns to add movement to the design, and thick makeup to Jeanne's face to \"make [her] feel like something out of the 1960s\". Though Shimazaki preferred Bayonetta, Jeanne turned out to be the more popular of the two witches among Kamiya and the development team.<ref name=\"pg-designing2\" /> Still, in an April 2009 interview, Kamiya called the former \"in many ways&nbsp;... my ideal woman\".<ref name=\"gamespot-qanda\" />\n\nThough the game's director \"deliberately created ''Bayonetta'' from scratch\" and has called its story \"completely original\", he has admitted using \"some names from [[Norse mythology|Scandinavian mythology]]\" and playing \"about half of\" ''[[Devil May Cry 4]]'' for research.<ref name=\"gamespot-qanda\" /> As a fan of folk music, he named Bayonetta's set of four handguns after the old English ballad \"[[Scarborough Fair (ballad)|Scarborough Fair]]\", and its individual guns Parsley, Sage, Rosemary and Thyme.<ref name=\"gi-scarborough\">{{Cite magazine|last= |first= |title=''Bayonetta'': Hair-raising |magazine=Game Informer |volume=190 |publisher=GameStop |date = February 2009|page=63}}</ref><ref name=\"1up-interview-scarborough\">{{harvnb|Mielke|2008|p=1}}. \"1UP: What are the names of her weapons? HK: As a set, they're all Scarborough Fair. Parsley, Sage, Rosemary, Thyme...\"</ref>  Hiroshi Yamaguchi focused on composing music for the game that had a \"nice up-tempo beat\" and expressed femininity through female [[choir]]s, pianos, and other {{\" '}}beautiful' instruments\"\u2014though some tracks also use pure orchestra or [[folk instrument]]s<ref name=\"pg-music\">{{cite web |last=Yamaguchi |first=Hiroshi |url=http://platinumgames.com/2009/05/29/the-music-of-bayonetta/ |title=The Music of Bayonetta |publisher=PlatinumGames |date=May 29, 2009 |accessdate=October 11, 2009 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090908003847/http://platinumgames.com/2009/05/29/the-music-of-bayonetta/ |archivedate=September 8, 2009 }}</ref>\u2014while Kenichiro Yoshimura transformed Shimazaki's Bayonetta design into a game model and used the [[digital sculpting]] tool [[ZBrush]] to create [[normal mapping|normal maps]] for its details. He worked with Shimazaki on the model's makeup, referred to foreign models with similar bodies, and said that he \"really wanted to get Bayonetta's backside perfect\" because I guess I am into that sort of thing...\"<ref name=\"gspy-bottom\">{{cite web |last=Williams |first=Bryn |url=http://xbox360.gamespy.com/xbox-360/bayonetta/976133p1.html |title=Bayonetta's Perfect Bottom |publisher=GameSpy |date=April 24, 2009 |accessdate=October 15, 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090427074510/http://xbox360.gamespy.com/xbox-360/bayonetta/976133p1.html |archive-date=April 27, 2009 |url-status = live }}</ref><ref name=\"pg-modeling\">{{cite web |last=Yoshimura |first=Kenichiro |url=http://platinumgames.com/2009/04/24/modeling-bayonetta/ |title=Modeling Bayonetta |publisher=PlatinumGames |date=April 24, 2009 |accessdate=October 10, 2009 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090427075943/http://platinumgames.com/2009/04/24/modeling-bayonetta/ |archivedate=April 27, 2009 }}</ref> The language spoken by the Angels and for all Infernal Summons is [[Enochian]], a divine language described by [[John Dee]] and his colleague [[Edward Kelley]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://platinumgames.com/2009/12/11/butmoni-coronzon-from-the-mouth-of-the-witch/ |title=Archived copy |accessdate=October 8, 2015 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150910021857/http://platinumgames.com/2009/12/11/butmoni-coronzon-from-the-mouth-of-the-witch/ |archivedate=September 10, 2015 }}</ref>\n\nDuring development, five difficulty modes were created: \"Very Easy\", \"Easy\", \"Normal\", \"Hard\", and \"Non-Stop Infinite Climax\".<ref name=\"1up-handson\" /> On Easy and Very Easy, a \"Very Easy Automatic\" mode is made available in which the game positions Bayonetta to perform attacks on enemies, and the player only needs to press one button to execute elaborate combos, unless they wish to perform their own choice of movements or attacks. Kamiya, who first added such a mode to ''Devil May Cry'', posted a video on the game's official website in which character designer Mari Shimazaki demonstrated the mode (which Kamiya \"jokingly called 'Mommy Mode{{' \"}}) in ''Bayonetta''.<ref name=\"1up-onebutton\">{{cite web |last=Bailey |first=Kat |url=http://www.1up.com/do/newsStory?cId=3175753 |title=PlatinumGames Shows Off Bayonetta's 'Very Easy Automatic' Mode |website=1UP.com |date=August 24, 2009 |accessdate=October 10, 2009 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121012213033/http://www.1up.com/news/platinum-games-shows-bayonetta-easy |archivedate=October 12, 2012 }}</ref><ref name=\"pg-buttonconfig\">{{cite video |people=Kamiya, Hideki (interviewee); Kellams, JP (interviewer) |url=http://platinumgames.com/2009/10/02/hideki-kamiya-answers-your-questions/ |title=Hideki Answers Vol. 2 Part 1! |publisher=PlatinumGames |format=Adobe Flash |time=0:23\u20131:00 and 3:33\u20133:40 |date=April 24, 2009 |accessdate=October 10, 2009 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091010143938/http://platinumgames.com/2009/10/02/hideki-kamiya-answers-your-questions/ |archivedate=10 October 2009 |url-status = dead }}</ref> He expected players to first complete the game in 10 to 12 hours, but believed that its rating system (similar to that of ''Viewtiful Joe'', which he directed) and the pursuit of high scores provide [[replay value]].<ref name=\"gi-marchiafava\" /> The game has a fixed button configuration; Kamiya said \"we found that there wasn't really a point to changing [it].\"<ref name=\"pg-buttonconfig\" />\n\nTo Kamiya, the core theme of the game and its protagonist's attacks is \"sexiness\".<ref name=\"gi-marchiafava\" /><ref name=\"1up-interview-sexiness\">{{harvnb|Mielke|2008|p=5}}. \"So the whole, the theme of her attacks is 'sexiness.'&nbsp;... I'm having fun with the team thinking, 'So what should we do with Bayonetta to make her look sexy?' And they're like, 'Oh, maybe this move might be good. This motion might be good.' So that's what we're thinking right now.\"</ref> To fit the theme of \"her femininity and sexuality\", the developers made Bayonetta bleed rose petals instead of blood when hit, and used butterfly imagery as part of her moves and outfit.<ref name=\"ign-exposed\">{{cite web |last=Shea |first=Cam |url=http://xbox360.ign.com/articles/103/1030290p1.html |title=Bayonetta Exposed! |publisher=IGN |page=2 |date=September 30, 2009 |accessdate=December 24, 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091004194105/http://xbox360.ign.com/articles/103/1030290p1.html |archive-date=October 4, 2009 |url-status = live }}</ref><ref name=\"pg-theworld2\">{{cite web |last=Nakamura |first=Ikumi |url=http://platinumgames.com/2009/08/28/the-world-of-bayonetta-2/ |title=The World of Bayonetta\u20142 |publisher=PlatinumGames |date=August 28, 2009 |accessdate=December 24, 2009 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100102172729/http://platinumgames.com/2009/08/28/the-world-of-bayonetta-2/ |archivedate=2 January 2010 |url-status = dead }}</ref> Her giant boot, fist, and monster attacks reveal some of her body\u2014her hair is magically formed into clothes but must be stripped from her body to form these attacks - and when the player targets an enemy, red lips mark the enemy's chest; this led [[IGN]] to call the developing game a mix of \"action and a great big helping of [[fan service]]\".<ref name=\"ign-progress\" />\n\n==Promotion==\n[[File:Yea, it's just one of those days (3597475152).jpg|thumb|[[Penny Drake]] dressed as the character at [[E3 2009]]]]\n\nAt the 2009 [[Electronic Entertainment Expo]] (E3), Sega chose [[Penny Drake]] to model as Bayonetta after auditioning 100 women.<ref name=\"usatoday-e3model\">{{cite video |people=Kessler, Michelle |url=http://content.usatoday.com/communities/gamehunters/post/2009/06/67685135/1 |title=Video: Bringing Bayonetta to life |work=[[USA Today]] |format=Adobe Flash |date=June 5, 2009 |accessdate=October 15, 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091114034314/http://content.usatoday.com/communities/gamehunters/post/2009/06/67685135/1 |archive-date=November 14, 2009 |url-status = live }} (A [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=S1Mu5yEpDYs higher quality version] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160415001140/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=S1Mu5yEpDYs |date=2016-04-15 }} of the video is available on [[YouTube]].)</ref> The company then joined men's lifestyle website [[Dennis Digital|Maxim.com]] to run a contest to find women who looked like Bayonetta. The grand prize winner, Andrea Bonaccorso, announced on November 23, 2009, received an Xbox 360, a 50-inch [[plasma television]], and a copy of the 360 version of the game.<ref name=\"kotaku-bebayonetta\">{{cite web |last=Crecente |first=Brian |authorlink=Brian Crecente |url=http://kotaku.com/5350789/be-bayonetta-win-hd-gaming-set+up |title=Be Bayonetta, Win HD Gaming Set-Up |website=Kotaku |date=September 2, 2009 |accessdate=October 11, 2009 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091006215626/http://kotaku.com/5350789/be-bayonetta-win-hd-gaming-set%2Bup |archivedate=6 October 2009 |url-status = live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=SEGA Announces Winner Of The Bayonetta Model Competition Hosted at Maxim |url=http://xbox360.ign.com/articles/104/1048850p1.html |publisher=IGN |date=November 23, 2009 |accessdate=November 23, 2009 | archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20091126040127/http://xbox360.ign.com/articles/104/1048850p1.html| archivedate= 26 November 2009 <!--DASHBot-->|url-status = live}}</ref> Sega hired Japanese pop singer [[MiChi]] to perform \"Something Missing\", written for a ''Bayonetta'' commercial.<ref name=\"andria-michi\">{{cite web |last=Gantayat |first=Anoop |url=http://www.andriasang.com/e/blog/2009/08/26/michi_bayonetta |title=MiChi to Perform Bayonetta Theme Song |publisher=andriasang.com |date=August 26, 2009 |accessdate=October 10, 2009 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090830105908/http://www.andriasang.com/e/blog/2009/08/26/michi_bayonetta |archivedate=August 30, 2009 }}</ref> The commercial, which has since been shown on the game's official Japanese website, touts the game as \"{{Nihongo|non-stop climax action|\u221e\u30af\u30e9\u30a4\u30de\u30c3\u30af\u30b9\u30fb\u30a2\u30af\u30b7\u30e7\u30f3}}\" and features a model dressed as Bayonetta with a lollipop.<ref name=\"bayonetta-jp\">{{cite video |url=http://bayonetta.jp/ |title=<nowiki>Bayonetta\u2014\u30d9\u30e8\u30cd\u30c3\u30bf | Official Website</nowiki> |publisher=Sega |format=Adobe Flash |accessdate=October 10, 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110222215622/http://bayonetta.jp/ |archive-date=February 22, 2011 |url-status = live }}</ref> In the U.S. and the UK, commercials have featured [[La Roux]]'s \"[[In for the Kill (song)|In for the Kill]]\".<ref>{{cite web |last=Hashimoto |first=Yusuke |url=http://platinumgames.com/2010/01/04/bayonetta-tv-commercial |title=Bayonetta TV commercial |publisher=[[PlatinumGames]] |date=January 4, 2010 |accessdate=January 17, 2010 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100205171513/http://platinumgames.com/2010/01/04/bayonetta-tv-commercial/ |archivedate=5 February 2010 |url-status = dead }}</ref>\n\n==Release and merchandise==\n[[Game demo|Demos]] of ''Bayonetta'' were released on [[Xbox Live]] and [[PlayStation Network]] in Japan on October 8, 2009,<ref name=\"g4tv-demoreleased\">{{cite web|last=Klepek |first=Patrick |url=http://g4tv.com/thefeed/blog/post/699848/bayonetta-demo-released-for-xbox-360-playstation-3in-japan.html |title=Bayonetta Demo Released For Xbox 360, PlayStation 3...In Japan |publisher=[[G4 (U.S. TV channel)|G4]] |date=October 8, 2009 |accessdate=December 22, 2009 }}</ref> and internationally on December 3, 2009.<ref name=\"cvg-demoreleased\">{{cite web|last=CVG Staff |url=http://www.computerandvideogames.com/article.php?id=228769 |title=News: Bayonetta demo launches: Videos |work=[[Computer and Video Games#Website|ComputerAndVideoGames.com]] |publisher=[[Future plc]] |date=December 3, 2009 |accessdate=December 22, 2009 | archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100104061933/http://computerandvideogames.com/article.php?id=228769| archivedate= 4 January 2010 <!--DASHBot-->|url-status = live}}</ref><ref name=\"joystiq-demoreleased\">{{cite web |last=Nelson |first=Randy |url=http://www.joystiq.com/2009/12/03/psn-thursday-classic-call-of-duty-bayonetta-demo-beckon |title=PSN Thursday: Classic Call of Duty, Bayonetta demo beckon |website=[[Joystiq]] |date=December 3, 2009 |accessdate=December 22, 2009 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091207113501/http://www.joystiq.com/2009/12/03/psn-thursday-classic-call-of-duty-bayonetta-demo-beckon |archivedate=7 December 2009 |url-status = dead }}</ref> The game was released on October 29, 2009, in Japan,<ref name=\"pg-bayorelease\">{{cite web |last=Hashimoto |first=Yusuke |url=http://platinumgames.com/2009/11/06/bayonetta-released-in-japan/ |title=Bayonetta Released in Japan |publisher=PlatinumGames |date=November 6, 2009 |accessdate=November 9, 2009 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100119032228/http://platinumgames.com/2009/11/06/bayonetta-released-in-japan/ |archivedate=January 19, 2010 |url-status = dead }}</ref><ref name=\"sega-bayorelease\">{{cite web|url=http://blog.bayonetta.jp/archives/1125 |title='Bayonetta' Finally Released!! (\u3064\u3044\u306b\u300cBAYONETTA(\u30d9\u30e8\u30cd\u30c3\u30bf)\u300d\u767a\u58f2!!) |publisher=Sega |language=Japanese |date=October 29, 2009 |accessdate=October 29, 2009 | archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20091101104200/http://blog.bayonetta.jp/archives/1125| archivedate= 1 November 2009 <!--DASHBot-->|url-status = live}}</ref> and was later released in other regions in 2010: January 5 in North America, January 7 in Australia, and January 8 in Europe.<ref name=\"ign-releasedates\">{{cite web |last=Reilly |first=Jim |url=http://xbox360.ign.com/articles/104/1040376p1.html |title=Sega Confirms Bayonetta Release Date |publisher=IGN |date=October 29, 2009 |accessdate=December 22, 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091101143026/http://xbox360.ign.com/articles/104/1040376p1.html |archive-date=November 1, 2009 |url-status = live }}</ref> An update for the PlayStation 3 version was released on January 28, allowing players to install the game on their hard drive, dramatically reducing load times.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://kotaku.com/5457808/ps3-version-of-bayonetta-getting-update |title=PS3 Version of Bayonetta Getting Update |website=Kotaku |date=January 26, 2010 |accessdate=June 24, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121013084508/http://kotaku.com/5457808/ps3-version-of-bayonetta-getting-update |archive-date=October 13, 2012 |url-status = live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |author=Contact Michael McWhertor: Comment |url=http://kotaku.com/5458852/bayonetta-updated-for-ps3-load-times-improved |title=Bayonetta Updated For PS3, Load Times Improved |website=Kotaku |date=January 28, 2010 |accessdate=June 24, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121013084515/http://kotaku.com/5458852/bayonetta-updated-for-ps3-load-times-improved |archive-date=October 13, 2012 |url-status = live }}</ref>\n\nA 150-song, five-CD soundtrack for the game was scheduled for a November 4 release.<ref name=\"kotaku-soundtrack\">{{cite web |last=Ashcraft |first=Brian |url=http://kotaku.com/5363044/bayonetta-getting-5+disc-cd-soundtrack |title=Bayonetta Getting 5-Disc CD Soundtrack |website=Kotaku |date=September 18, 2009 |accessdate=October 10, 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090923194310/http://kotaku.com/5363044/bayonetta-getting-5+disc-cd-soundtrack |archive-date=September 23, 2009 |url-status = live }}</ref> Another soundtrack CD, ''Rodin's Selection'', was created for inclusion with pre-ordered copies of the game. It comes packaged in a brown jacket styled as a menu from Rodin's bar \"The Gates of Hell\".<ref name=\"1up-rodin\">{{cite web |last=Gifford |first=Kevin |url=http://www.1up.com/do/newsStory?cId=3175177 |title=Bayonetta Dated, Merchandised Out |website=1UP.com |date=July 15, 2009 |accessdate=October 15, 2009 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110604155917/http://www.1up.com/news/bayonetta-dated-merchandised |archivedate=June 4, 2011 |url-status=dead}}</ref> Sega of Europe released an ''\u221e Climax Edition'' of the game in the UK, France, Spain, and Australia, which included the game, the ''Rodin's Selection'' tracks packaged in a black-and-red jacket with the game logo, and an artbook. Pre-orders in Australia and \"most European territories\" included a replica of one of Bayonetta's \"Scarborough Fair\" guns.<ref name=\"pg-climaxedition\">{{cite web |last=Nakamura |first=Ikumi |url=http://platinumgames.com/2009/11/25/bayonetta-japanese-pre-order-bonus-rodins-selection-original-soundtrack/ |title=Bayonetta Japanese Pre-Order Bonus \u2013 Rodin's Selection (Original Soundtrack) |publisher=PlatinumGames |date=November 25, 2009 |accessdate=December 23, 2009 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091217103914/http://platinumgames.com/2009/11/25/bayonetta-japanese-pre-order-bonus-rodins-selection-original-soundtrack/ |archivedate=17 December 2009 |url-status = dead }}</ref><ref name=\"siliconera-climaxedition\">{{cite web|author=Spencer |title=Bayonetta: Climax Edition Weaving Into Europe |url=http://www.siliconera.com/2009/11/10/bayonetta-climax-edition-weaving-into-europe/ |website=Siliconera |date=November 10, 2009 |accessdate=November 10, 2009 | archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20091113163009/http://www.siliconera.com/2009/11/10/bayonetta-climax-edition-weaving-into-europe/| archivedate= 13 November 2009 <!--DASHBot-->|url-status = live}}</ref><ref name=\"segaau-climaxedition\">{{cite press release|url=http://www.sega-australia.com/news/?n=3650 |title=Pre-order Bayonetta Special Edition |publisher=Sega |date=November 26, 2009 |accessdate=December 27, 2009 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110904065406/http://www.sega.com/news/?n=3650 |archivedate=September 4, 2011 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n''Bayonetta: Witch of Vigrid'', a book with pictures of the title character and an \"interview\" with her, was released on October 22, 2009.<ref name=\"kotaku-artbook\">{{cite web|last=Ashcraft |first=Brian |url=http://kotaku.com/5359473/bayonetta-the-photo-book |title=Bayonetta The Photo Book |website=Kotaku |date=September 15, 2009 |accessdate=October 11, 2009 | archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20091003214203/http://kotaku.com/5359473/bayonetta-the-photo-book| archivedate= 3 October 2009 <!--DASHBot-->|url-status = live}}</ref> By then, a ''Bayonetta'' theme had been made available for the [[Google Chrome]] browser.<ref name=\"kotaku-chrometheme\">{{cite web|last=Glasser |first=AJ |url=http://kotaku.com/5377704/you-got-lombax-bayonetta-and-monkey-in-my-chrome |title=You Got Lombax, Bayonetta And Monkey In My Chrome |website=Kotaku |date=October 9, 2009 |accessdate=October 10, 2009 | archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20091011230623/http://kotaku.com/5377704/you-got-lombax-bayonetta-and-monkey-in-my-chrome| archivedate= 11 October 2009 <!--DASHBot-->|url-status = live}}</ref> A song entitled \"Reaping Beauty\" by [[MC Lars]] and featuring Beefy, Random, [[Tina Root]] of Small Halo and SMP was included on the second re-release of Lars' album ''[[21 Concepts (But a Hit Ain't One)]]''. The song is inspired by ''Bayonetta'', and heavily references the title character and many of the game's aesthetic and gameplay elements.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.warpzoned.com/?p=7958 | first = John | last = Scalzo | title = MC Lars' b-side collection 21 Concepts (featuring the Bayonetta song) now available | date = 2011-05-18 | accessdate = 2011-05-18 | publisher = Warp Zoned | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20120322143246/http://www.warpzoned.com/?p=7958 | archive-date = 2012-03-22 |url-status = live }}</ref>\n\nOn April Fools' Day, April 1, 2017, Sega released ''8-bit Bayonetta'' for free on [[Microsoft Windows]]. While the game uses [[8-bit era]] graphics and was simplified in gameplay, only allowing Bayonetta to jump and fire at a few enemies and considered part of the April Fools' Day pranks, players found several bits of pieces in the achievements that pointed to a countdown timer on Sega's website ending on April 11, 2017, as well as other data mining suggesting a possible port of the ''Bayonetta'' game to Windows.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.polygon.com/2017/4/3/15161058/bayonetta-teaser-steam-pc | title = Sega\u2019s hinting at something, and it sure looks like Bayonetta | first = Allegra | last = Frank | date = April 3, 2017 | accessdate = April 11, 2017 | work = [[Polygon (website)|Polygon]] | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20170412061808/http://www.polygon.com/2017/4/3/15161058/bayonetta-teaser-steam-pc | archive-date = April 12, 2017 |url-status = live }}</ref> At the end of the timer, it was confirmed that ''Bayonetta'' was coming to Windows, supporting 4K graphics and other improvements from the original versions.<ref name=bayo-pc>{{cite web|last1=Romano|first1=Sal|title=Bayonetta coming to PC with 4K support today|url=http://gematsu.com/2017/04/bayonetta-coming-pc-4k-support-today|website=Gematsu|accessdate=11 April 2017|date=11 April 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web | url = http://www.vg247.com/2017/04/11/bayonetta-out-on-steam-today-with-4k-support-and-advanced-graphics-options/ | title = Bayonetta out on Steam today with 4K support and advanced graphics options | first = Stephany | last = Nunneley | date = April 11, 2017 | accessdate = April 11, 2017 | work = [[VG247]] | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20170412030546/http://www.vg247.com/2017/04/11/bayonetta-out-on-steam-today-with-4k-support-and-advanced-graphics-options/ | archive-date = April 12, 2017 |url-status = live }}</ref> A spokesperson for Platinum Games said that they have become interested in porting more of their games to PC, though the decision to do so has been a choice of their respective publishers; Sega has been supportive of personal computer releases as of late. Platinum's development efforts to port the game to the [[Wii U]] aided in the completion of the PC port.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.pcgamer.com/bayonetta-is-out-now-on-pc-we-spoke-to-platinum-about-making-it-happen/ | title = Bayonetta is out now on PC, we spoke to Platinum about making it happen | first = Joe | last = Donnelley | date = April 12, 2017 | accessdate = April 12, 2017 | work = [[PC Gamer]] | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20170412225621/http://www.pcgamer.com/bayonetta-is-out-now-on-pc-we-spoke-to-platinum-about-making-it-happen/ | archive-date = April 12, 2017 |url-status = live }}</ref>\n\nTo celebrate the game's tenth anniversary, Sega announced a ''Bayonetta & Vanquish 10th Anniversary Bundle'' compilation for the [[PlayStation 4]] and [[Xbox One]]. The retail release includes a steelbook and ''Bayonetta'', alongside another PlatinumGames title ''[[Vanquish (video game)|Vanquish]]'', on a single disc, with support for [[4K resolution|4K]] 60[[Frames per second|fps]] visuals for PlayStation 4 Pro and Xbox One X users. Both games can also be purchased digitally either individually or collectively at a discount price. The ''10th Anniversary Bundle'' was released on February 18, 2020.<ref name=\"IGN cites 10th anniversary release\">{{cite news |last1=Plant |first1=Logan |title=Bayonetta, Vanquish Double Pack Coming in 2020 to PS4, Xbox One |url=https://www.ign.com/articles/2019/12/09/bayonetta-vanquish-double-pack-coming-in-2020-to-ps4-xbox-one |work=[[IGN]] |date=December 9, 2019 |accessdate=December 10, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Soundtrack===\nThe ''Bayonetta Original Soundtrack'' was released in Japan on November 4, 2009. The album contains five discs with 150 tracks used in the game, composed by Hiroshi Yamaguchi, Masami Ueda, Rei Kondoh, Takayasu Sodeoka, [[Norihiko Hibino]], [[Takahiro Izutani]], Yoshitaka Suzuki, Erina Niwa, and Naoto Tanaka. It was also released on the North American [[iTunes Store]] on the same day, spanning five Volumes in total. The North American release of the soundtrack does not include any version of \"[[Fly Me To The Moon]]\". [[Helena Noguerra]] provided the main vocals for the theme of Bayonetta.<ref name=\"segaeu-climaxedition\">{{cite web |last=\"Martin\u2014the fat ninja\" |url=http://blogs.sega.com/europe/2009/11/10/bayonetta-special-edition-revealed/ |title=Bayonetta Special Edition revealed |publisher=Sega Europe |date=November 10, 2009 |accessdate=December 23, 2009 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100411024851/http://blogs.sega.com/europe/2009/11/10/bayonetta-special-edition-revealed/ |archivedate=April 11, 2010 }}</ref>\n\n===''Bayonetta: Bloody Fate''===\n{{Main|Bayonetta: Bloody Fate}}\n\nAn [[anime]] film based on the game, titled {{nihongo|''Bayonetta: Bloody Fate''|\u30d9\u30e8\u30cd\u30c3\u30bf \u30d6\u30e9\u30c3\u30c7\u30a3\u30d5\u30a7\u30a4\u30c8|Beyonetta Buraddi Feito}}, was directed by Fuminori Kizaki and produced by [[Gonzo (studio)|Gonzo]], with screenplay by Mitsutaka Hirota and character designs by Ai Yokoyama. The film was announced at [[Tokyo Game Show]] 2013 and released in ten Japanese theaters for two weeks on November 23, 2013.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2013-09-18/bayonetta-game-gets-anime-film-by-gonzo-in-november |title=Bayonetta Game Gets Anime Film by Gonzo in November |publisher=Anime News Network |accessdate=2013-10-16 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131016075544/http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2013-09-18/bayonetta-game-gets-anime-film-by-gonzo-in-november |archive-date=2013-10-16 |url-status = live }}</ref> It was then released on Blu-ray Disc and DVD in Japan on January 24, 2014. A [[manga]] adaptation illustrated by Mizuki Sakakibara was published in two parts in [[Kodansha]]'s ''[[Bessatsu Sh\u014dnen Magazine]]'' on November 9, 2013 and December 9, 2013 respectively.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2013-11-08/bayonetta/bloody-fate-anime-gets-manga-blu-ray/dvd-date |title=Bayonetta: Bloody Fate Anime Gets Manga, Blu-ray/DVD Date |publisher=Anime News Network |date=2013-11-08 |accessdate=2014-08-19 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140808114712/http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2013-11-08/bayonetta/bloody-fate-anime-gets-manga-blu-ray/dvd-date |archive-date=2014-08-08 |url-status = live }}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n{{Video game reviews\n<!-- Aggregators -->\n| MC = PS3: 87/100<ref name=\"MC_PS3\">{{cite web |url=https://www.metacritic.com/game/playstation-3/bayonetta |title=Bayonetta for PlayStation 3 Reviews |website=[[Metacritic]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |accessdate=April 25, 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190203201520/https://www.metacritic.com/game/playstation-3/bayonetta |archivedate=February 3, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref><br />X360: 90/100<ref name=\"MC_X360\">{{cite web |url=htt